    <h2 style="margin-top: 0;">Chapter 16: Building Custom Nodes</h2>

    <h3>When To Build a Custom Node</h3>
    <p>We've already seen that n8n offers multiple ways to integrate with external systems. So when should we actually
        write a custom TypeScript node from scratch instead of just using an HTTP Request or a Sub-Workflow?</p>

    <table class="comparison-table">
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Approach</th>
                <th>Best For</th>
                <th>Setup Time</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>HTTP Request Node</strong></td>
                <td>One-off API calls, internal endpoints.</td>
                <td>2 minutes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Sub-Workflow</strong></td>
                <td>Reusable logic combining multiple API calls.</td>
                <td>10 minutes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Custom Node</strong></td>
                <td>Providing a beautiful UI for non-technical users to access our proprietary internal API.</td>
                <td>~1-2 days</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="tip-box">
        <strong>💡 Tip:</strong> If we are the only developers using the n8n canvas, stick to the HTTP Request node. We
        only build custom nodes when we want to abstract away API complexity (like handling pagination or tricky OAuth
        handshakes) so our marketing or operations team can drag-and-drop our internal API just like they do with
        Stripe.
    </div>

    <h3>Project Structure &amp; Dev Environment</h3>
    <p>n8n provides a starter template exactly for this purpose. We don't start from a blank folder. Instead, we clone
        their starter repo which comes pre-configured with TypeScript, ESLint, and the n8n compiler scripts.</p>

    <p>A typical node repository (often named <code>n8n-nodes-mycompany</code>) looks like this:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">n8n-nodes-mycompany/
├── package.json
├── credentials/
│   └── MyApiApi.credentials.ts    # Defines how users authenticate
└── nodes/
    └── MyApi/
        ├── MyApi.node.ts          # The core logic and UI definitions
        └── GenericFunctions.ts    # Helper functions for making HTTP calls</code></pre>

    <p>During development, we need a way to run n8n locally while it watches our TypeScript files for changes. We
        achieve this by linking our local repo using <code>npm link</code>.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <strong>⚠️ Warning:</strong> Avoid writing nodes in plain JavaScript. n8n relies heavily on TypeScript
        interfaces (like <code>INodeType</code>) to extract UI definitions during the build step. Without TypeScript,
        the build process will fail.
    </div>

