    <h3>Returning Items Correctly</h3>
    <p>Inside the <code>execute</code> method, we loop over the incoming items, process our API calls, and return the
        mutated data. We must return an array containing an array of <code>INodeExecutionData</code> objects. This
        matches n8n's internal data model.</p>

    <p>Here is a real example of the execution logic for our internal API node:</p>

    <pre><code class="language-typescript">async execute(this: IExecuteFunctions): Promise&lt;INodeExecutionData[][]&gt; {
    const items = this.getInputData();
    const returnData: INodeExecutionData[] = [];

    // Loop over every item entering the node
    for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) {
        try {
            const operation = this.getNodeParameter('operation', i) as string;
            
            if (operation === 'getUser') {
                const userId = this.getNodeParameter('userId', i) as string;
                
                // Fetch our credentials to grab the API key
                const credentials = await this.getCredentials('myApiApi');
                
                // We use n8n's built-in this.helpers.request to handle the HTTP call
                const response = await this.helpers.request({
                    method: 'GET',
                    url: `https://api.mycompany.com/users/${userId}`,
                    headers: {
                        'Authorization': `Bearer ${credentials.apiKey}`
                    },
                    json: true,
                });

                // Wrap the API response in n8n's expected JSON structure
                returnData.push({ json: response });
            }
        } catch (error) {
            // Handle error logic: If "Continue on Fail" is set, don't crash
            if (this.continueOnFail()) {
                returnData.push({ json: { error: error.message } });
                continue;
            }
            throw error;
        }
    }

    return [returnData];
}</code></pre>

    <div class="usage-box">
        <strong>Important:</strong> Notice how we loop through <code>items.length</code>. A node might receive 1 item
        from a Webhook, or 500 items from a Postgres trigger. We must process <em>each item individually</em> in the
        <code>execute</code> loop to ensure data consistency.
    </div>

    <h3>Publishing &amp; Community Nodes</h3>
    <p>Once we have built and tested our node locally, we can publish it as standard Node packages to <code>npm</code>.
        Community nodes are simply npm packages prefixed with <code>n8n-nodes-</code>.</p>

    <p>To install a community node in our production n8n instance (like Docker), we can go to <strong>Settings &rarr;
            Community Nodes</strong> in the n8n UI, input the npm package name, and n8n will automatically download and
        install it into our running instance.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <strong>⚠️ Warning:</strong> When self-hosting via Docker Compose, installing via the UI works, but destroys
        immutability. If the container crashes and rebuilds, the node is gone. Make sure to define community nodes
        directly in our <code>docker-compose.yml</code> or bake them into a custom Dockerfile via
        <code>RUN npm install -g n8n-nodes-mycompany</code>.
    </div>

